Change-Id: I778e62bb4541516a0702bf4f28dab05472bc5af0","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/ce01bc97daa9fcbabcf7b9a5a797e854aed5d2e0"},{"sha":"c8e732d973dc972ab24ad46ac1f6364160f00ea8","author":{"email":"a33a2701f6790f0a44360bcc1a194138e928e0d3@google.com","name":"Alexander Belyaev"},"message":"[tfrt:jit] Split the current output fusion into two parts.

The first part occurs when tiling the reduction. As a result we have two output arguments in the tiled_loop: one provides the initial values for the reduction result and the other is an init_tensor operation that will be used to initialize the temporary result (reduction of a single tile).

The second part happens after the padding/peeling. It sinks the init_tensor introduced in the first stage into the loop body and gets rid of the output operands for the intermediate results.

[{"sha":"e5a86e1df1b19c6a5b1935f8fc3c499614d795cb","author":{"email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com","name":"Taehee Jeong"},"message":"PR #50615: [TFLite] Avoid passing negative quantized multipliers to MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/50615

Hello,

This PR updates the SUB and DIV kernels to avoid passing negative quantized multipliers to the `MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier` method.

It allows us to later on add a restriction on the quantized multiplier of the int32 `MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier` similar to the one already present in the int64 version.

Thibaut

--
b65f25db31e47adb02da0375ed2c75ac01ca7686 by Thibaut Goetghebuer-Planchon <thibaut.goetghebuer-planchon@arm.com>:

Update SUB operator tests to have different scaling in the inputs and outputs

The change provides a more in-depth testing of the SUB operator. Previously the same scaling was used for both inputs and for the output, a simple subtraction in the kernel without any rescaling would have made the tests pass.

[{"sha":"274df9b02330b790aa8de1cee164b70f72b9b244","author":{"email":"02bd3f004a63c78990e4cfa97922eaaaa6d78ea5@google.com","name":"Dan Moldovan"},"message":"Clean up placer rules.

This change uses type information to determine whether a node without HostMemory outputs returns (variant) data types known to only exist on the host, such as datasets. Mainly, such nodes include common ops like Identity, control flow, etc, as most other dataset-specific nodes have HostMemory annotations in their kernel registrations.

This method is more robust because we no longer need to match op names by substring checks, and it avoids inefficient DFS searches in this pass.

[{"sha":"9d258510d1740c71aed3d626482c7609a58e1581","author":{"email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com","name":"Ran Chen"},"message":"#tf2xla Support lower cross partition collectives

XLA collectives have four differeng group modes (kCrossReplica, kCrossPartition, kCrossReplicaAndPartition, kFlattenedID). The mode is decided by the combination of channel_id and use_global_device_ids.

Since TF collectve ops don't have a suitable counterpart of channel_id, the change adds a mode attribute to tf.xla_all_reduce, and sets channel_id according to the mode during lowering.

use_global_device_ids is not exposed in mhlo dialect, so we only support kCrossReplica and kCrossReplicaAndPartition to start with.

This is to prepare integrate collective v3 ops with XLA. A later will first lower v3 collective ops to tf2xla collective ops, then leverage the existing tf2xla collective ops lowering.
